<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,858,1027]" pageId="4" pageNumber="329">
This species was transferred to 
<taxonomicName box="[508,649,859,883]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Azaleothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="329" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[508,649,859,883]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="329">Azaleothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
despite the fact that it remains known from a single female on which few structural details can be seen (
<bibRefCitation author="Mound" box="[534,770,894,919]" pageId="4" pageNumber="329" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Tree, D. J. (2014) Generic relationships of two obscure Australian Thysanoptera species described by A. A. Girault. Australian Entomologist, 41 (4), 205 - 210." type="journal article" year="2014">
Mound &amp; Tree 
<number box="[709,770,895,919]" pageId="4" pageNumber="329" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). However, the maxillary stylets are long and close together medially, the postocular setae are very short and more widely expanded than in any other known member of this genus, and antennal segments VII and VIII are completely fused. The single female was collected in 
<date box="[1286,1436,967,991]" pageId="4" pageNumber="329" value="1929-01">
January 
<number box="[1380,1436,967,991]" pageId="4" pageNumber="329" value="1929.0">1929</number>
</date>
at Brisbane, Queensland.
</paragraph>
